{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774410494,"nonce":"Atn0QkDXycROSK2ocvi/V9Stjas=","title":"Variable reach length: implications for adversarial training and SISU detection","message":"## Summary\n\nCurrent decision: constant reach length (0.5 units) for the SISU velocity modulation experiments. This issue tracks the future move to variable reach lengths and the considerations involved.\n\n## Why constant length for now\n\nThe SISU-conditional velocity signal has been \u003c1% across all conditions tested. Variable reach lengths add confounds:\n- Optimal speed, perturbation vulnerability, and adversarial strategy all depend on reach length\n- A length-dependent SISU effect would average out across trials\n- The adversary must jointly learn perturbation strategy as function of (length, SISU, movement phase) — harder optimization\n\nConstant length keeps the adversary's problem stationary and maximizes signal-to-noise for detecting the velocity modulation.\n\n## Considerations for variable length\n\nWhen the mechanism is demonstrated under constant length, variable length reaches test generalization:\n- Does the controller learn a length-invariant robust policy?\n- Does the SISU-velocity effect scale with reach length?\n- Does the adversary develop length-conditional strategies?\n\n### Length distribution choice\n- Normal distribution: occasional very long reaches, which may have different dynamics\n- Uniform in a range (e.g., [0.3, 0.7]): bounded, predictable\n- The reach length affects trial difficulty non-linearly (short reaches are easy, long reaches stress the controller more under perturbation)\n\n### Adversarial training interaction\nWith variable length, the adversary's optimal perturbation timing shifts: for short reaches, late perturbation (near target) is most disruptive; for long reaches, mid-movement perturbation (during high-velocity phase) may be worse. The adversary must learn to condition on reach length, adding a dimension to its input space.\n\n### Trial duration\nConstant length + constant duration = fixed speed requirement. Variable length + constant duration = model must scale speed with distance (an additional task). Variable length + variable duration = complicates batching.\n\n## Cross-references\n- Bug: be3804f — Translation invariance in inputs\n- Bug: 61d3502 — Experimental plan\n- Bug: 3b70482 — SISU velocity puzzle","files":null}]}